        <h1>üîÑ Agile & Scrum Methodologies</h1>

        <h2>Agile Principles</h2>

        <h3>The Agile Manifesto</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Individuals and interactions</strong> over processes and tools</li>
            <li><strong>Working software</strong> over comprehensive documentation</li>
            <li><strong>Customer collaboration</strong> over contract negotiation</li>
            <li><strong>Responding to change</strong> over following a plan</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Key Values</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Iterative development</li>
            <li>Continuous feedback and improvement</li>
            <li>Self-organizing teams</li>
            <li>Adaptive planning</li>
            <li>Early and frequent delivery</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Scrum Framework</h2>

        <h3>Scrum Roles</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Product Owner:</strong> Defines features, prioritizes backlog, accepts work</li>
            <li><strong>Scrum Master:</strong> Facilitates process, removes blockers, coaches team</li>
            <li><strong>Development Team:</strong> Cross-functional, self-organizing, 5-9 members</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Scrum Events</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Sprint (2-4 weeks):</strong> Fixed time-box for completing backlog items
                <ul>
                    <li>Typical duration: 2 weeks for most teams</li>
                    <li>Goal: Deliver potentially shippable increment</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Sprint Planning:</strong> Define sprint goal and select backlog items
                <ul>
                    <li>Duration: ~2 hours per week of sprint</li>
                    <li>Output: Sprint backlog</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Daily Standup (15 min):</strong> Synchronize activities
                <ul>
                    <li>What did I do yesterday?</li>
                    <li>What will I do today?</li>
                    <li>Any blockers?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Sprint Review:</strong> Demo completed work to stakeholders
                <ul>
                    <li>Duration: ~1 hour per week of sprint</li>
                    <li>Gather feedback for next sprint</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Sprint Retrospective:</strong> Reflect on process improvements
                <ul>
                    <li>What went well?</li>
                    <li>What didn't go well?</li>
                    <li>What should we improve?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Scrum Artifacts</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Product Backlog:</strong> Prioritized list of features/requirements
                <ul>
                    <li>User stories with acceptance criteria</li>
                    <li>Ordered by business value</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Sprint Backlog:</strong> Items committed to current sprint
                <ul>
                    <li>Plus tasks to complete them</li>
                    <li>Updates daily</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Increment:</strong> Sum of all completed items
                <ul>
                    <li>Must be in usable condition</li>
                    <li>Meets Definition of Done</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>User Stories & Estimation</h2>

        <h3>Writing User Stories</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Format:</strong> "As a [role], I want [feature], so that [benefit]"</li>
            <li><strong>Example:</strong>
                <pre>As a security analyst,
I want to filter vulnerabilities by severity,
So that I can focus on the most critical issues first.

Acceptance Criteria:
- Filter dropdown with LOW, MEDIUM, HIGH, CRITICAL options
- Results update in real-time
- Filter state persists across page refreshes
- Show count of filtered results</pre>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Story Points & Estimation</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Fibonacci Scale:</strong> 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21
                <ul>
                    <li>1-2: Simple tasks (few hours)</li>
                    <li>3-5: Medium complexity (1-2 days)</li>
                    <li>8-13: Complex features (3-5 days)</li>
                    <li>21+: Should be broken down</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Planning Poker:</strong> Team estimation technique
                <ul>
                    <li>Each member selects a card privately</li>
                    <li>All reveal simultaneously</li>
                    <li>Discuss differences, re-vote until consensus</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Velocity:</strong> Average story points completed per sprint
                <ul>
                    <li>Used for capacity planning</li>
                    <li>Improves over first few sprints</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Working in R&D Environments</h2>

        <h3>Key Differences from Traditional Development</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Ambiguity:</strong> Requirements are exploratory, not fixed</li>
            <li><strong>Experimentation:</strong> Many approaches may fail before finding the right one</li>
            <li><strong>Pivots:</strong> Direction changes based on learnings</li>
            <li><strong>Minimal Direction:</strong> High autonomy and self-direction required</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Thriving with Minimal Direction</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Proactive Communication:</strong> Don't wait to be told what to do
                <ul>
                    <li>Ask clarifying questions early</li>
                    <li>Share progress frequently</li>
                    <li>Raise concerns immediately</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Take Ownership:</strong> Drive your initiatives
                <ul>
                    <li>Propose solutions, not just problems</li>
                    <li>Research independently</li>
                    <li>Make informed decisions</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Rapid Prototyping:</strong> Build, test, learn, iterate
                <ul>
                    <li>Create MVPs to validate assumptions</li>
                    <li>Gather feedback early and often</li>
                    <li>Don't over-engineer initially</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Cross-Functional Collaboration</h2>

        <h3>Working with Product Teams</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Understand business goals and user needs</li>
            <li>Challenge requirements constructively</li>
            <li>Suggest technical alternatives</li>
            <li>Provide realistic estimates</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Working with Security Experts</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Learn domain language (CVE, CVSS, OWASP)</li>
            <li>Ask "why" to understand context</li>
            <li>Translate technical constraints clearly</li>
            <li>Involve them early in design decisions</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Global Team Collaboration</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Asynchronous communication best practices
                <ul>
                    <li>Document decisions in writing</li>
                    <li>Over-communicate context</li>
                    <li>Use video recordings for complex topics</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Timezone considerations
                <ul>
                    <li>Find overlap hours for meetings</li>
                    <li>Rotate meeting times fairly</li>
                    <li>Use async tools (Slack, Notion, Confluence)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Code Reviews</h2>

        <h3>Giving Feedback</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Be respectful and constructive</li>
            <li>Explain the "why" behind suggestions</li>
            <li>Distinguish between must-fix and nice-to-have</li>
            <li>Praise good patterns and solutions</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Receiving Feedback</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Don't take it personally</li>
            <li>Ask for clarification if unclear</li>
            <li>Learn from every review</li>
            <li>Say thank you</li>
        </ul>

